⚠️ Things that could still cost you points in a live demo:
Real contract addresses — your .env has the registry addresses but VALIDATOR_ADDRESS, RISK_ROUTER_ADDRESS, and CAPITAL_VAULT_ADDRESS still say fallback/placeholder values. If the hackathon gives you real deployed contracts, plug those in.

AWS credentials — your .env has your_aws_access_key as placeholder. Without real AWS keys, the brain falls back to simulated decisions instead of actually calling Nova. Judges will notice if it's not hitting the real AI.

Funded Sepolia wallet — your private key needs test ETH to actually send registration/feedback transactions. Without gas, the on-chain calls fail silently and the dashboard shows "⚠️ Local" instead of "✅ On-Chain".

No live DEX execution — the bot signs intents but doesn't actually swap tokens. This is fine for the hackathon (it's about trust, not trading), but be ready to explain it.

Bottom line:
Your code is 100% spec-compliant. The architecture is solid. What separates a winning demo from a "nice try" is:

Real AWS keys so Nova actually thinks
Real test ETH so transactions actually land on Sepolia
A smooth 3-minute demo showing: register → analyze → sign → execute → see reputation update → show audit trail
